<LEADPARA>  SATURDAY was the 100th anniversary of basketball's creation. On the afternoon
of Dec. 21, 1891, a physical education professor in Massachusetts named James
Naismith nailed a peach basket to a wall and bounced a soccer ball onto the
floor.;   And on the afternoon of Dec. 21, 1991, at Toso Pavilion, the
basketball teams of San Jose State and Santa Clara commemorated the event by
nailing each other with elbows -- and bouncing their torsos off the floor, the
basket supports, the bleachers and anything else that was handy.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STILL A PEACH OF A GAME  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     And <ORGANIZATION>San Jose State</ORGANIZATION> came from behind to score a ragged and rugged 61-60
victory.;   "The game is 100 years old today?" asked Spartans Coach <PERSON>Stan
Morrison</PERSON> afterward. "Well, we set it back 50 years.";   Not entirely true.
<DATE>Saturday</DATE>'s game hardly was an outright dog. The drama was thick. <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION>
and <LOCATION>San Jose State</LOCATION> were two struggling teams, trying to find their stride
early in the season. The Broncos are still searching. At the final buzzer,
<LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION> forward <PERSON>Rhea Taylor</PERSON> was lying flat on his back in agony, pounding
his fists on the hardwood after he missed the final shot. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION>San Jose
State</ORGANIZATION>'s players hugged and yelped at center court.;   In short, it was like
the finish of thousands -- millions? -- of basketball games played over the
<DATE>last century</DATE>. It was why the game has lasted so long and become so much a part
of our sports landscape. <DATE>Saturday</DATE> was an occasion to toast all of that,
although <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION> was not in the mood. The Broncos, with all five starters
back from last season, are 2-6.;   "The 100th anniversary, huh?" said <PERSON>Carroll
Williams</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION>'s head coach, then added in sarcastic frustration: "It's
a great game, isn't it? A great game.";   The sport's centennial has not drawn
the attention here that it has in other places, because the <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION> is
nowhere close to being a hoops hotbed, the Warriors' current exalted state
aside. Of the 25 largest college basketball arenas, none is located in
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION>. And only 1,425 spectators showed up for <DATE>Saturday</DATE>'s game.;   But
that doesn't mean <DATE>Saturday</DATE>'s historical moment should pass without mention.
Today, worldwide, basketball is more omnipresent than ever. And the recent
success of the women's teams at <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION> indicates the sport
may be entering a whole new level of popularity.;   Yet it gives one pause.
What if <ORGANIZATION>Naismith</ORGANIZATION> hadn't been able to find a peach basket that fateful day in
<DATE>1891</DATE>? Or what if he'd slipped on the ice, broken his hip, and had never made
it to the gym? Would we now be spending the winter watching <ORGANIZATION>ESPN</ORGANIZATION> telecasts of
<LOCATION>Big East</LOCATION> croquet? Or curling?;    "I CAN'T imagine what the world would be
like without basketball," <PERSON>Morrison</PERSON> said. "In my view, it's right up there with
the invention of the wheel. Without basketball, I don't know what I would be
doing right now. I would probably be a teacher, I guess. Or an architect.";  
At least one of <DATE>Saturday</DATE>'s players was pondering the same thoughts. As he
packed his duffel bag after the game, the Spartans' <PERSON>Terry Cannon</PERSON> proudly
pulled out a certificate that the <ORGANIZATION>American Basketball Congress</ORGANIZATION> has sent to
every college player this year, commemorating their appearance in the
centennial.;   "Basketball isn't just a sport for some people, it's a
lifestyle, a livelihood," said <ORGANIZATION>Cannon</ORGANIZATION>. "It's allowed me to receive an
education and allowed others to earn a living by teaching it.";   A major
cultural force, in other words. From small-town driveways, to big-city
playgrounds, to <LOCATION>Toso Pavilion</LOCATION> on a <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>. Happy birthday, hoops.
You've earned the right to party.  </TEXT>
