<LP>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- Huffy Corp. Chairman Harry A. Shaw III,
crediting strong mountain bike sales, said he's comfortable
with analysts' estimates of fourth quarter earnings of 25
cents to 27 cents a share.
   In the 1990 fourth quarter, Huffy earned $1 million, or 12
cents a share, on sales of $121.4 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON> said he also agrees with analysts who expect
<ORGANIZATION>Huffy</ORGANIZATION> to report <DATE>1991</DATE> earnings of as much as <MONEY>$1.41</MONEY> a share. In
<DATE>1990</DATE>, the bicycle and consumer products company earned <MONEY>$18
million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>$1.28</MONEY>. He expects <DATE>1991</DATE> sales to come in at <MONEY>$675
million</MONEY> to <MONEY>$678 million</MONEY>, compared with <MONEY>$517 million</MONEY> in <DATE>1990</DATE>.
   Moreover, <PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON> expects the sales growth trend to
continue, with <DATE>1992</DATE> sales projected to reach between <MONEY>$725
million</MONEY> and <MONEY>$750 million</MONEY>.
   Mountain bike sales have driven much of <ORGANIZATION>Huffy</ORGANIZATION>'s growth,
and now represent <PERCENT>60%</PERCENT> of the company's total bicycle sales,
up from <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> four years ago. To maintain sales growth, the
company plans to unveil a new line of bicycles combining
heavy-duty features of mountain bicycles and standard
lighter-weight 10-speed touring bikes.
   "They're for somebody who's not riding a lot off-road,"
<PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON> said. The new line will be priced in the <MONEY>$119</MONEY>-<MONEY>$200</MONEY>
range, while its current line of mountain bikes sell for
between <MONEY>$119</MONEY> and <MONEY>$300</MONEY>. <ORGANIZATION>Huffy</ORGANIZATION> is planning a national
television advertising campaign to push the new line in <DATE>April</DATE>
and <DATE>May</DATE>.
   True <ORGANIZATION>Temper Hardware</ORGANIZATION>, which <ORGANIZATION>Huffy</ORGANIZATION> acquired from <ORGANIZATION>Black &amp;
Decker Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>November 1990</DATE>, started <DATE>1991</DATE> "slowly" but had
a "terrific" <DATE>fourth quarter</DATE> and <DATE>December</DATE>, <PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON> said.
Sales were especially strong in a new line of childrens'
garden tools and adult pruning tools, including shears and
clippers. <ORGANIZATION>Huffy</ORGANIZATION> expects the hardware subsidiary will have a
"very strong <DATE>January</DATE> and a very good first quarter."
   Less impressive were results in the company's inventory
counting subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION>Washington Inventory Service</ORGANIZATION>. The unit
has suffered management turnover in recent years, but has
stabilized under new leadership. "We're hoping the <DATE>first
quarter</DATE> will be an improvement over last year," <PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON>
said. Its <ORGANIZATION>Huffy Service First</ORGANIZATION> unit lost a major customer,
representing <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>15%</PERCENT> of the tiny unit's <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY> to <MONEY>$2
million</MONEY> annual earnings, when the customer decided to do its
own retail store displays and products. Still, <PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON>
expects the unit to grow in <DATE>1992</DATE> as more retailers contract
out for display and product assemblage.
   Sales of basketball backboards grew last year, thanks to
the continuing popularity of the <ORGANIZATION>National Basketball
Association</ORGANIZATION>, whose name the company licenses, <PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON> said.
A big seller was a stand-alone water-filled backboard system
for residential recreational use.
   Last fall, the company also introduced 25 juvenile
products, which helped boost sales of products such as car
seats, room monitors and baby carriers by <PERCENT>15%</PERCENT>, <PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON> said.
<ORGANIZATION>Huffy</ORGANIZATION> expects to introduce about as many new juvenile
products this year.
   <PERSON>Mr. Shaw</PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION>Huffy</ORGANIZATION> is in an active acquisition mode.
"We're looking for another consumer durable-product company
that's undermarketed, as we felt True Temper was." Of
particular interest to <ORGANIZATION>Huffy</ORGANIZATION> are companies, both domestic and
overseas, in the hardware, houseware, lawn and garden, and
juvenile products businesses.
</TEXT>
